postcontent: Designed by John Browning, the Model 1911 was the standard-issue side arm for the United States armed forces from 1911 to 1985 and is still carried by some U.S. forces today. The Model 1911's longevity is due to Browning's often-imitated design, which incorporates the short recoil principle. The M1911 is a single-action, semi-automatic, magazine-fed, and recoil-operated handgun chambered for the .45 ACP cartridge. While many manufacturers have produced this firearm, Colt is the original and the most trusted. This 1918-manufactured pistol is in NRA fine condition.

title: For Sale:  Mossberg 930 Semi-Auto 12 ga Shotgun
postcontent:
I have for sale a very good condition Mossberg 930 Slugster.  This shotgun is 12 gauge and has a rifled barrel for shooting Sabot slugs.  If you want to use it for home defense or bird hunting, just pick up another barrel and swap it out.  This was my deer hunting gun last year but this year I now have a .44 Magnum rifle so I no longer need this.  It functions flawlessly.  It has a 24" ported barrel for reduced muzzle rise and holds 4+1 without the plug and 2+1 with the plug installed.  I have upgraded the magazine spring to a higher powered Wolff spring and upgraded the follower to a GG&G steel/aluminum follower for more reliable feeding.  The barrel has an integrated cantilever scope base ready to mount a scope of your choice.  The stock is a monte carlo style and is polymer.  I have also added a shell holder on the stock to carry an extra 5 shells.  This shotgun will shoot 2 3/4" and 3" shells.  It has a spacer system to adjust the drop angle of the stock.  It also has a quick empty button that will release all of the loaded shells with the press of the button.  I have the original box, owner's manual, lock, the stock magazine spring and magazine follower, as well as an extra recoil pad and a Limbsaver recoil pad.  I am also including 3 boxes of Sabot slugs to get you started.  I had this out hunting 1 day last year and dropped a deer in its tracks with it at 60 yards.  This is a great deer gun, I just no longer need it.

Asking $550 obo for everything.  Located in the Dublin/Hilliard area of Northwest Columbus.  NOT interested in trades at this time.  Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  W. JENKS RIFLE-1844
postcontent: VERY UNIQUE! W. Jenks .54 Cal Ball, breechloading percusion, black powder rifle- of year 1844. Marked U.S.N./RP/P. Serial number 14.  William Jenks entered into a contract with the Navy on September 22, 1845 for 1,000 of his carbines to be equipped with the Maynard tape priming device . He had four previous Navy contracts dating from 1841 to 1846 for about 4,250 of his initial side hammer percussion "mule ear" carbines. These earlier weapons were manufactured by N.P. Ames of Springfield, Mass. from 1841 to 1846. In 1846, the final contract was purchased from Ames along with William Jenks, personally and most of the carbine making equipment by E. Remington of Herkimer N.Y. who completed the contract obligations. Remington then filled the contract of September 22, 1845 calling for 1,000 Maynard tape equipped carbines. These arms were not a conversion of the original Jenks carbines, but wholly new carbines with the inventor himself supervising the entire production of this well made and handsome arm.

title: For Sale:  1931 Springfield 1903 - Collector Grade
postcontent:
Up for sale is my 1931 manufactured Springfield 1903 Military rifle.

Serial # 1,369,xxx dates the nickel steel receiver to 1931. Barrel is original to the rifle and marked SA (Springfield) and dated 2/31 with the flaming bomb ordinance symbol. Stock is the original "S" stock cartouched "SA" over "SPG" for Stanley P. Gibbs who was the small arms inspector at Springfield starting in 1931.

This rifle is in original 1931 condition and was never rebuilt. Stock, receiver, and barrel all date 1931 and are original. Very fine condition overall. Vintage WWII leather sling included. Action is superb and bore is very fine. Fit and finish are excellent. 

Springfield production numbers were very low in the early 1930's as the Great Depression was in full swing and there were many '03's left over from WW1. As a result, in 1931 production was very limited and quality extremely high. Many National Match rifles were made during this time frame. This is a beautiful example of their production capability at that time. 

Springfield started using nickel steel receivers around serial # 1,250,000 making these later  model's the pinnacle of original 1903 development prior to the much more common WWII 1903A3 models.

$1450 cash, no trades. Private sale, must be legal to own and have proper ID

I can email more pics if needed. Located in Frisco.

Text me at 214 215-8six3six for more info

Thanks,
